{
  "text": "Future models will examine the impact of selection on growth as a production trait. This will allow us to evaluate IgE as a marker of resistance. The IgE-mediated hypersensitivity response is associated with reduced larval establishment [CITATION_1] but is weakly associated with reduced growth [CITATION_2] . Binding of parasite molecules to IgE induces mast cell degranulation which breaks down the tight junction between epithelial cells and induces a relative protein deficiency [CITATION_3] . Therefore, IgE is less attractive as a marker than IgA, which is not associated with reduced growth rate [CITATION_4] . In future work, we will extend the model to allow growth to depend on worm number and IgE activity. We will then be able to contrast selection schemes that use growth, IgA and IgE to identify the optimal combination of markers.",
